<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b>PART I</b></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b><u>ITEM 1.&nbsp; BUSINESS</u></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>&nbsp;</u></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><u>Restatement of Historical
Financial Statements</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal><i>Overview</i></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Petroleum
Development Corporation (&quot;PDC&quot; or the &quot;Company&quot;) is the Managing General
Partner for PDC 2004-A Limited Partnership (the &quot;Partnership&quot;).&nbsp; The Managing
General Partner manages all of the Partnership's exploration and production
activities, accounting, and reporting requirements.&nbsp; The Partnership has no
employees and all accounting and reporting has been performed by the
Partnership's Managing General Partner and its staff.&nbsp; For disclosures in this
Form 10-K, the management and officers of the Partnership refers to management
and officers of the Managing General Partner.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>This Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended
December 31, 2005, includes the financial statements of the Partnership for the
year ended December 31, 2005, and amends and restates the previously filed
financial statements as of and for the period from April 30, 2004 (date of
inception) through December 31, 2004, and the financial statements for each of
the quarters since inception in 2004 through the quarter ended March 31, 2005.
&nbsp;&nbsp;As previously announced in a Current Report on Form 8-K as filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission (&quot;SEC&quot;) on November 14, 2005, and
August 24, 2005, and in an update included in Form 12b-25 filed with the SEC on
April 3, 2006, the Company identified that the Partnership's accounting for
derivatives, asset retirement obligations and certain aspects of its accounting
for oil and gas properties, were accounted for improperly and needed to be
restated. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>In
light of this restatement, readers should no longer rely on our previously
filed financial statements and other financial information for 2004 and each of
the quarters since inception in 2004 through the quarter ended March 31, 2005.&nbsp;
</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Our
restatement of the financial statements for the periods identified above is
presented in a comprehensive format within this Form 10-K for the year ended
December 31, 2005, and in the financial statements included in Item 8
&quot;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data.&quot;&nbsp; Substantially all of the
information for the quarters and year-to-date periods ended June 30, 2005, and
September 30, 2005, that are normally contained in Quarterly Reports on Form
10-Q have instead been incorporated and presented in this Form 10-K.&nbsp; We intend
to file our Form 10-Q reports for the quarters ended March 31, June 30, and
September 30, 2006, as soon as practicable after the filing of this Form 10-K.&nbsp;
</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
following tables set forth a summary of the adjustments for the restatement and
their impact on net income for the period from April 30, 2004 through December
31, 2004, and for the three months ended March 31, 2005.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-4-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>




<p class=MsoNormal><i>Material Weaknesses and
Accounting Issues</i></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership has evaluated the effectiveness of the design and operation of its
disclosure and control procedures.&nbsp; During 2005, the Partnership determined
that there were errors in previously filed financial statements which required
a restatement of the financial statements.&nbsp; As a result of this review of
accounting procedures and policies, the Partnership concluded that, as of
December 31, 2005, disclosure controls and procedures were not effective to
ensure that information required to be disclosed in the reports filed under the
Exchange Act are recorded, processed, summarized, and reported within the time
periods specified in the SEC's rules and forms.&nbsp; </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>During
2005, the Partnership identified material
weaknesses related to its policies and procedures and
technical expertise in U.S. generally accepted accounting principles to ensure
the preparation of accurate and reliable interim and annual financial
statements. Specifically, the Partnership lacked personnel with sufficient technical
accounting and financial reporting expertise and also lacked policies and
procedures in place to determine and document the appropriate application of
accounting principles. These deficiencies impacted the Partnership's accounting
for derivatives, asset retirement obligations and depreciation, depletion and
amortization, and resulted in more than a remote likelihood that a material
misstatement of the annual or interim financial statements would not be
prevented or detected.&nbsp; </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>To
address the material weaknesses, we performed additional analyses and other
post-closing procedures to ensure that the financial statements were prepared
in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles.&nbsp; Accordingly,
management of the Partnership believes that the financial statements included
in this report fairly present in all material respects the Partnership's
financial position, results of operations and cash flows for the periods
presented.&nbsp; See Item 9A. &quot;Controls and Procedures&quot; for information concerning these
material weaknesses.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>For
additional information relating to the effect of our restatement, see the
following items:</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9679;&nbsp;&nbsp;Item 6.&nbsp; Selected Financial Data</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9679;&nbsp;&nbsp;Item 7 and 7A.&nbsp; Management's Discussion
and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operation</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#9679;&nbsp;&nbsp;Item 8.&nbsp; Financial Statements and
Supplementary Data</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>General</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal>The Partnership was organized
as a limited partnership pursuant to the West Virginia Uniform Limited
Partnership Act for the purpose of aggregating funds for the exploration and production
of oil and natural gas.&nbsp; Business operations of the Partnership commenced on
April 30, 2004, upon the closing of the offering for the sale of the
partnership units. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Pursuant
to a registration statement filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
limited and general partnership interests were registered for an offering under
the PDC 2004-2006 Drilling Program for the formation of a series of limited
partnerships.&nbsp; The Partnership was formed with total capital contributions of
$29,030,865 from limited partners and additional general partners
(collectively, the &quot;Investor Partners&quot;) and $6,419,029 in capital contributed
by the Managing General Partner. Total funding of the Partnership was $35,449,894.&nbsp;
The capital contributions from the Investor Partners consisted of 1,451.54
partnership units at a unit price of $20,000 each. After syndication costs of
$2,919,286 and a one time management fee to the Managing General Partner of
$435,463, the Partnership had available cash of $32,095,145 to commence
Partnership activities for the drilling of natural gas and oil wells. During
2005, all additional general partners were converted to limited partners under
provisions of the Partnership Agreement. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Under
the terms of the Partnership Agreement, the allocation of production revenues
among the Investor Partners and the Managing General Partner is as follows:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Operating
and direct costs are allocated and charged to the Investor Partners and the
Managing General Partner in the same percentages as revenues are allocated.&nbsp;
See &quot;Note 4 - Allocation of Partners' Interests&quot; in the Notes to the Financial
Statements for a complete description of the allocation of all Partnership
revenues and costs.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Drilling Activities</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Since
its formation, the Partnership has been engaged in onshore, domestic oil and
natural gas exploration and production exclusively in the Rocky Mountain
Region. The Partnership participated in drilling only development wells. Due to
natural gas being the predominant production, all wells are classified as gas
wells although significant amounts of oil can be produced in association with
the gas.&nbsp; The following table summarizes the Partnership's drilling activities
during 2004 related to its thirty-seven wells:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:9.0pt;text-indent:-9.0pt'>Additional information concerning the Partnership's
gas wells is contained in &quot;Item 2 - Properties&quot; below.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Plan of Operations</u></p>



<p class=MsoBodyText>Under agreement with the Investor Partners, the Managing
General Partner serves as operator for the drilling of the Partnership's wells
and for the production and sale of natural gas and oil from the wells. Once producing, the Partnership's wells will be
produced until they are depleted or until they are uneconomical to produce.&nbsp;
PDC plans to recomplete the Codell formation in most of the wells in the
Wattenberg Field after 5 or more years of production because these wells will
usually have experienced a significant decline in production in that time
period.&nbsp; These Codell recompletions typically increase the production rates and
recoverable reserves.&nbsp; Prior experience of PDC and other producers with Codell
recompletions has resulted in significant production increases for most wells,
although not all recompletions have been successful. The cost of a
Codell recompletion is about one-third of the cost of a new well (currently
about $180,000). &nbsp;The Managing General Partner will arrange for contractors to
perform the work, the cost of which will be paid out of overall revenues of the
Partnership.&nbsp; PDC will pay its proportionate share of costs based on the
operating costs sharing ratios of the Partnership.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Employees</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership has no employees.&nbsp; Services to the Partnership are provided by PDC,
which has a total of approximately 170 employees including personnel in
accounting and finance, administration, engineering, geology, field operations,
and natural gas marketing. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Markets for Oil and Gas</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
availability of a market for any oil and natural gas produced from the
operation of the Partnership's wells will depend upon a number of factors
beyond the control of the Partnership which cannot be accurately predicted.&nbsp;
These factors include the proximity of the Partnership wells to and the
capacity of natural gas pipelines, the availability and price of competitive
fuels, fluctuations in seasonal supply and demand, and government regulation of
supply and demand created by its pricing and allocation restrictions.&nbsp;
Oversupplies of gas can be expected to occur from time to time and may result
in the Partnership's wells being shut-in or production being curtailed.&nbsp;
Increased imports of oil and natural gas have occurred and are expected to
continue.&nbsp; The effects of such imports could adversely impact the market for
domestic oil and natural gas. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-6-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>




<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>PDC
utilizes the services of its wholly-owned subsidiary, Riley Natural Gas (RNG),
in marketing the oil and natural gas produced from Partnership wells.&nbsp; RNG has
been in the gas marketing business since 1986. All oil and natural gas is sold under contracts based on market
sensitive indexes that vary from month to month. No fixed price contracts are
in place. &nbsp;Purchase contracts for the
sale of oil are cancelable on 30 days notice, whereas purchase contracts for
the sale of natural gas may range from spot market sales of short duration to
contracts with a term of a number of years and that may require the dedication
of the gas from a well for a period ranging up to the life of the well.&nbsp; PDC
will not make any commitment of future production that does not primarily
benefit the Partnership.&nbsp; RNG is entitled to charge reasonable fees for its
services, including out-of-pocket costs, which will be equal to or less than
fees charged to non-affiliated producers for similar services.&nbsp; The Partnership sold its oil and natural gas to three
customers which accounted for 58%, 28% and 14% of the Partnership's total oil
and natural gas sales in 2005 and 57%, 25% and 18% in 2004.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Derivatives and Hedging
Activities</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal>Historically, PDC and RNG
have utilized commodity based derivative instruments to manage a portion of the
exposure to price volatility stemming from natural gas and crude oil
production.&nbsp; In order to provide a more predictable cash flow stream, PDC
expects to continue the use of derivative instruments including the
Partnership's production of natural gas and oil, and will enter into derivative
contracts on behalf of the Partnership.&nbsp; PDC may use financial hedges, put
options, call options, and other derivative instruments to offset variations in
prices.&nbsp; The contracts hedge committed and anticipated natural gas and oil
sales generally forecasted to occur within the next two-year period. The
Managing General Partner does not hold or issue derivatives for trading or
speculative purposes and permits utilization of hedges only if there is an
underlying physical position.&nbsp; See &quot;Commodity Price Risk&quot; under Item 7A in
this Form 10-K.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Competition</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership competes in marketing its gas and oil with numerous companies and
individuals, many of which have financial resources, staffs and facilities
substantially greater than those of the Partnership or PDC.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Governmental Regulations</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Federal
and state regulatory authorities have established rules and regulations
requiring permits for well operations, reclamation bonds and reports concerning
operations.&nbsp; States also have statutes and regulations concerning the spacing
of wells, environmental matters and conservation, and have established
regulations concerning the unitization and pooling of oil and gas properties
and maximum rates of production from oil and gas wells. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><u>Natural Gas Regulation</u>.&nbsp; Sale of natural gas by the Partnership is subject
to regulation of production, transportation and pricing by governmental
regulatory agencies.&nbsp; Generally, the regulatory agency in the state where a
producing well is located regulates production activities and, in addition, the
transportation of gas sold intrastate.&nbsp; The Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission (FERC) regulates the operation and cost of interstate pipeline
operators who transport gas.&nbsp; Currently, the price of gas sold by the
Partnership is not regulated by any state or federal agency.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><u>Environmental and Safety Regulations</u>.&nbsp; The Partnership believes that it complies, in all
material respects, with all legislation and regulations relating to
environmental and safety matters in the drilling and production of oil and gas
wells and the discharge of wastes.&nbsp; Compliance with such provisions and
regulations is significant during well development but has not had a material
effect upon the Partnership's expenditures for capital equipment, its
operations or its competitive position.&nbsp; The cost of such compliance is not
anticipated to be material in the future.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership believes it has complied in all material respects with applicable
state and federal regulations.&nbsp; The Partnership spent approximately $176,000 in
2004 for expenditures related primarily to environmental permitting and
compliance; the amounts spent in 2005 are deemed not material.&nbsp; </p>









<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-7-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>




<p class=MsoNormal><b><u>ITEM 1A.&nbsp; RISK FACTORS </u></b></p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify;text-indent:0in'>In the course of its normal business, the
Partnership is subject to a number of risks that could adversely impact its
business, operating results, financial condition, and cash distributions.&nbsp; The
following risk factors should be considered carefully in addition to the other
information included in this report.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Drilling natural gas and oil wells is
speculative and may be unprofitable or result in the total loss of investment. The drilling and completion operations undertaken
by the Partnership for the development of natural gas and oil reserves are
inherently speculative and involve a high degree of risk and the possibility of
a total loss of investment. Drilling activities may result in unprofitable well
operations, not only from non-productive wells, but also from wells that do not
produce natural gas or oil in sufficient quantities or quality to return a profit
on the amounts expended.&nbsp; Consequently, Partnership wells may not produce
sufficient natural gas and oil for investors to receive a profit or even to
recover their initial investment.&nbsp; Only three of the prior Partnerships
sponsored by PDC have, to date, generated cash distributions in excess of
investor subscriptions without tax savings.&nbsp; PDC cannot predict whether any
prospect will produce commercial quantities of natural gas or oil.&nbsp; PDC cannot
predict the life and the ultimate production of any wells, and the actual lives
could differ from those anticipated.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>There will be no public market for
the units.&nbsp; The investment in the Partnership is illiquid, and as a result an
Investor Partner may not be able to sell his or her units.&nbsp; There is and will be no public market for the
units nor will a public market develop for the units.&nbsp; Investor Partners may
not be able to sell their Partnership interests or may be able to sell them
only for less than fair market value.&nbsp; A sale or transfer of units by an investor
requires PDC's prior written consent.&nbsp; For these and other reasons, an investor
must anticipate that he or she will have to hold his or her Partnership
interests indefinitely and will not be able to liquidate his or her investment
in the Partnership.&nbsp; Consequently, an investor must be able to bear the
economic risk of investing in the Partnership for an indefinite period of time.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>The additional general partners will
be individually liable for Partnership obligations and liabilities that arose
prior to conversion to limited partners (which can occur only after the
drilling completion operations are finished) that are beyond the amount of
their subscriptions, Partnership assets, and the assets of the Managing General
Partner.&nbsp; Under West Virginia law, the state
in which the Partnership has organized, general partners of a limited
partnership have unlimited liability with respect to the Partnership.&nbsp;
Therefore, the additional general partners of the Partnership will be liable
individually and as a group for all obligations and liabilities of creditors
and claimants, whether arising out of contract or tort or in the conduct of the
Partnership's operations, until such time as the additional general partners
are converted to limited partners.&nbsp; Under the Partnership Agreement, this
conversion is not scheduled to occur until the drilling and completion
operations are finished.&nbsp; Irrespective of conversion, the additional general
partners will remain fully liable for obligations and liabilities that arose
prior to conversion.&nbsp; Investors as additional general partners may be liable
for amounts in excess of their subscriptions, the assets of the Partnership
including insurance coverage, and the assets of the Managing General Partner. </p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>The Partnership may retain Partnership
revenues if needed for Partnership operations to fully develop the
Partnership's wells; if full development of the Partnership's wells proves
commercially unsuccessful, an investor might anticipate a reduction in cash
distributions.&nbsp; The Partnership utilized
substantially all available capital raised in the offering for the drilling and
completion of wells.&nbsp; In the future, PDC may wish to rework or recomplete
Partnership wells but PDC has not held money from the initial investment for
that future work.&nbsp; There is no assurance that future development of the
Partnership's wells will prove commercially successful and that the
further-developed Partnership wells will generate sufficient funds from
production to increase distributions to the investors to cover revenues
retained.&nbsp; If future development of the Partnership's wells is not commercially
successful, the use of funds retained from production revenues could result in
a reduction of cash distributions to the Investor Partners. </p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Increases in prices of oil and
natural gas have increased the cost of drilling and development and may affect
the performance of the Partnership in both the short and long term.&nbsp; In the current high price environment, most oil
and gas companies have increased their expenditures for drilling new wells.&nbsp;
This has resulted in increased demand and higher cost for leases, oilfield
services and well equipment.&nbsp; Because of these higher costs, the risk to the
Partnership of decreased profitability from future decreases in oil and natural
gas prices is increased.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 align=center style='text-align:center'>-8-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>


<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Reductions in prices of oil and
natural gas reduce the profitability of the Partnership's production
operations.&nbsp; Global economic conditions,
political conditions, and energy conservation have created unstable prices.&nbsp;
Revenues of the Partnership are directly related to natural gas and oil prices
for which PDC cannot predict.&nbsp; The prices for domestic natural gas and oil
production have varied substantially over time and by location, and are likely
to remain extremely unstable.&nbsp; Revenue from the sale of oil and natural gas
increases when prices for these commodities increase and declines when prices
decrease.&nbsp; These unpredictable price changes can occur rapidly and are not
within the control of the Partnership.&nbsp; A decline in natural gas and/or oil
prices would result in lower revenues for the Partnership and a reduction of
cash distributions to the partners of the Partnership.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>The high level of drilling activity
could result in an oversupply of natural gas on a regional or national level,
resulting in much lower commodity prices.&nbsp;
Recently, the natural gas market has been characterized by excess demand
compared to the supplies available, leading in general to higher prices for
natural gas.&nbsp; The high level of drilling, combined with a reduction in demand
resulting from higher prices, could result in an oversupply of natural gas.&nbsp; In
the Rocky Mountain region, rapid growth of production and increasing supplies
may result in lower prices and production curtailment due to limitations on available
pipeline facilities or markets not developed to utilize or transport the new
supplies.&nbsp; In both cases, the result would probably be lower prices for the
natural gas the Partnership produces, reduced profitability for the Partnership
and reduced cash distributions to the Investor Partners.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Sufficient insurance coverage may not
be available for the Partnership, thereby increasing the risk of loss for the
Investor Partners.&nbsp; It is possible that some
or all of the insurance coverage which the Partnership has available may become
unavailable or prohibitively expensive.&nbsp; In that case, PDC might elect to
change the insurance coverage.&nbsp; The additional general partners could be
exposed to additional financial risk due to the reduced insurance coverage and
due to the fact that additional general partners would continue to be
individually liable for obligations and liabilities of the Partnership.&nbsp;
Investor Partners could be subject to greater risk of loss of their investment
because less insurance would be available to protect the Partnership from
casualty losses.&nbsp; Moreover, should the Partnership's cost of insurance become
more expensive, the amount of cash distributions to the investors will be
reduced.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Through
their involvement in Partnership and other non-partnership activities, the
Managing General Partner and its affiliates have interests which conflict with
those of the Investor Partners; actions taken by the Managing General Partner
in furtherance of its own interests could result in the Partnership being less
profitable and a reduction in cash distributions to the investors.</u>&nbsp; PDC's continued active participation in oil and
natural gas activities for its own account and on behalf of other partnerships
organized or to be organized by PDC, and the manner in which Partnership
revenues are allocated, creates conflicts of interest with the Partnership.&nbsp;
PDC has interests which inherently conflict with the interests of the Investor
Partners.&nbsp; In operating the Partnership, the Managing General Partner and its
affiliates could take actions which benefit themselves and not the
Partnership.&nbsp; These actions could result in the Partnership's being less
profitable.&nbsp; In that event, an Investor Partner could anticipate a reduction of
cash distributions.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>The Partnership and other
partnerships sponsored by the Managing General Partner may compete with each
other for prospects, equipment, contractors, and personnel; as a result, the
Partnership may find it more difficult to operate effectively and profitably.&nbsp; During and after 2006, PDC plans to offer
interests in other partnerships to be formed for substantially the same
purposes as those of the Partnership.&nbsp; Therefore, a number of partnerships with
unexpended capital funds, including those partnerships formed before and after
the Partnership, may exist at the same time.&nbsp; The Partnership may compete for
equipment, contractors, and PDC personnel which may make it more difficult and
more costly to obtain services for the Partnership.&nbsp; In that event, it is
possible that the Partnership would be less profitable.&nbsp; Additionally, because
PDC must divide its attention in the management of its own affairs as well as
the affairs of over seventy-five limited partnerships PDC has organized in other
programs, the Partnership will not receive PDC's full attention and efforts at
all times.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>The Partnership's derivative
activities could result in reduced revenue compared to the level the
Partnership might experience if no derivative instruments were in place.&nbsp; The Partnership expects to use derivative
instruments to reduce the impact of price movements on revenue.&nbsp; While these
derivative instruments protect the Partnership against the impact of declining
prices, they also may limit the positive impact of price increases.&nbsp; As a
result, the Partnership may have lower revenues when prices are increasing than
might otherwise be the case, which may also reduce the Partnership's cash flows
and cash distributions to the Investor Partners.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 align=center style='text-align:center'>-9-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>


<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Hedging transactions have, in the
past, and may, in the future, impact our cash flow from operations.&nbsp; Our
commodity hedging may prevent us from benefiting fully from price increases and
may expose us to other risks.&nbsp; PDC will
enter into hedging arrangements to reduce the Partnership's exposure to
fluctuations in natural gas and crude oil prices and to achieve more
predictable cash flow.&nbsp; Although the Partnership's hedging activities may limit
the Partnership's exposure to declines in natural gas and crude oil prices,
these activities may also limit and have, in the past, limited, additional
revenues from increases in natural gas and crude oil prices.&nbsp; To the extent
that the Partnership has PDC engage in hedging activities to protect itself
from commodity price volatility, the Partnership may be prevented from
realizing the benefits of price increases above the levels of the hedges.&nbsp; </p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Additionally,
the hedging transactions PDC has entered into, or will enter into on behalf of
the partnership, may not adequately protect the Partnership from financial loss
due to circumstances such as:</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='margin-top:3.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;
margin-left:74.9pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in'>&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Highly volatile natural gas
and crude oil prices;</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='margin-top:3.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;
margin-left:74.9pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in'>&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Production being less than
expected; or</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='margin-top:3.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;
margin-left:74.9pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in'>&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A counterparty defaults on its
contractual obligations.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>A significant financial loss by the
Managing General Partner could result in PDC's inability to indemnify
additional general partners for personal losses suffered because of Partnership
liabilities.&nbsp; As a result of PDC's
commitments as Managing General Partner of several partnerships and because of
the unlimited liability of a general partner to third parties, PDC's net worth
is at risk of reduction if PDC suffers a significant financial loss.&nbsp; Because
PDC is primarily responsible for the conduct of the Partnership's affairs, as
well as the affairs of other partnerships for which PDC serves as managing
general partner, a significant adverse financial reversal for PDC could result
in PDC's inability to pay Partnership liabilities and obligations.&nbsp; The
additional general partners of the Partnership might be personally liable for
payments of Partnership's liabilities and obligations.&nbsp; Therefore, the Managing
General Partner's financial incapacity could increase the risk of personal
liability as an additional general partner because PDC would be unable to
indemnify the additional general partners for any personal losses suffered
arising from Partnership operations.</p>

<p class=DMBodyText5 style='text-align:justify'><u>The Managing General Partner
may not have sufficient funds or budget to repurchase limited partnership
units.</u>&nbsp; As a result of the Managing General Partner being a general partner
in several partnerships, the Partnership's net worth is at risk of reduction if
PDC suffers a significant financial loss.&nbsp; Because the investors may request
the Managing General Partner to repurchase the units in the Partnership,
subject to certain conditions and restrictions, a significant adverse financial
reversal could result in the Managing General Partner's inability to pay for
Partnership obligations or the repurchase of investor units.&nbsp; </p>

<p class=DMBodyText5 style='text-align:justify'><u>Fluctuating market
conditions and government regulations may cause a decline in the profitability
of the Partnership.</u>&nbsp; The sale of any natural gas and oil produced by the
Partnership will be affected by fluctuating market conditions and governmental
regulations, including environmental and safety standards set by state and
federal agencies.&nbsp; From time-to-time, a surplus of natural gas or oil may occur
in areas of the United States.&nbsp; The effect of a surplus may be to reduce the
price the Partnership receives for the natural gas or oil production, or to
reduce the amount of natural gas or oil that the Partnership may produce and
sell.&nbsp; As a result, the Partnership may not be profitable.&nbsp; Lower prices and/or
lower production and sales will result in lower revenues for the Partnership
and a reduction in cash distributions to the partners of the Partnership.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Environmental hazards involved in
drilling natural gas and oil wells may result in substantial liabilities for
the Partnership.&nbsp; There are numerous natural
hazards involved in the drilling of wells, including unexpected or unusual
formations, pressures, blowouts involving possible damages to property and
third parties, surface damages, personal injury or loss of life, damage to and
loss of equipment, reservoir damage, and loss of reserves.&nbsp; Uninsured
liabilities would reduce the funds available to the Partnership, may result in
the loss of Partnership properties, and may create liability for additional
general partners.&nbsp; The Partnership may become subject to liability for
pollution, abuses of the environment and other similar damages, and insurance
coverage may be insufficient to protect the Partnership against all potential
losses.&nbsp; In that event, Partnership assets would be used to pay personal injury
and property damage claims and the costs of controlling blowouts or replacing
destroyed equipment rather than for drilling activities.&nbsp; These payments would
cause an otherwise profitable partnership to be less profitable or unprofitable
and would result in a reduction of cash distributions to the partners of the
Partnership.</p>

<p class=TOCH3 align=center style='text-align:center'>-10-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>


<p class=TOCH3 style='text-align:justify'>Information concerning reserves and
future net revenues estimates is inherently uncertain.&nbsp; The accuracy of proved reserves estimates and estimated future net
revenues from such reserves is a function of the quality of available
geological, geophysical, engineering and economic data and is subject to
various assumptions, including assumptions required by the SEC relating to oil
and gas prices, drilling and operating expenses, and other matters. Although we
believe that the estimated proved reserves represent reserves that we are
reasonably certain to recover, actual future production, oil and gas prices,
revenues, taxes, development expenditures, operating expenses, and quantities
of recoverable oil and gas reserves will most likely vary from the assumptions
and estimates used to determine proved reserves. Any significant variance could
materially affect the estimated quantities and value of our oil and gas
reserves which in turn could adversely affect our cash flows, results of
operations, and the availability of capital resources. In addition, we may
adjust estimates of proved reserves to reflect production history, results of
exploration and development, prevailing oil and gas prices and other factors,
many of which are beyond our control. Downward adjustments to the estimated
proved reserves could require us to write down to the carrying value of our oil
and gas properties which would reduce earnings and our partners' equity. </p>

<p style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'>The
present value of proved reserves will not necessarily equal the current fair
market value of the estimated oil and gas reserves. In accordance with the
reserve reporting requirements of the SEC, the estimated discounted future net cash flows from proved reserves are based
on prices and costs as of the date of the estimate. Actual future prices and
costs may be materially higher or lower than those as of the date of the
estimate. The timing of both the production and the expenses with respect to
the development and production of oil and gas properties will affect the timing
of future net cash flows from proved reserves and their present value.</p>

<p style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><u>Seasonal
weather conditions may adversely affect the Partnership's ability to conduct
drilling, completion and production activities in some of the areas where we
operate</u>.&nbsp; Oil and natural gas
operations in the Rocky Mountains are adversely affected by seasonal weather
conditions. In certain areas, drilling and other oil and natural gas activities
are restricted or prevented by weather conditions for up to 6 months out of the
year. This limits operations in those areas and can intensify competition
during those months for drilling rigs, oil field equipment, services, supplies
and qualified personnel, which may lead to periodic shortages. These
constraints and the resulting shortages or high costs could delay operations
and materially increase operating and capital costs and therefore, adversely
affect profitability. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal><u>ITEM 1B.&nbsp; UNRESOLVED STAFF
COMMENTS</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal>None.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>A
development well is a well that is drilled close to and into the same formation
as wells which have already produced and sold oil or natural gas.&nbsp; An
exploratory well is one which is drilled in an area where there has been no oil
or natural gas production, or a well which is drilled to a previously untested
or non-producing zone in an area where there are wells producing from other
formations.&nbsp; Productive wells consist of producing wells and wells capable of
producing oil and gas in commercial quantities, including gas wells awaiting
pipeline connections to commence deliveries.&nbsp; A gross well refers to the number
of wells in which the Partnership has an interest.&nbsp; A net well refers to a
gross well multiplied by the percentage working interest in the wells owned by
the Partnership.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-11-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>




<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership has not participated in any exploratory wells.&nbsp; No additional
drilling activity is planned.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Production
</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>See
&quot;Item 7 - Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and
Results of Operations&quot; for information related to the Partnership's production
as of December 31, 2005. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Reserves</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>See
&quot;Note 7 - Supplemental Reserve Information (Unaudited)&quot; in the Financial
Statements for information related to the Partnership's oil and gas reserves as
of December 31, 2005.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Title to Properties</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership's interests in producing acreage are in the form of assigned direct
interests in leases. Such properties are subject to customary royalty interests
generally contracted for in connection with the acquisition of properties and
could be subject to liens incident to operating agreements, liens for current
taxes, and other burdens.&nbsp; The Partnership believes that none of these burdens
materially interfere with the use of such properties in the operation of the
Partnership's business.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>As
is customary in the oil and gas industry, little or no investigation of title
is made at the time of acquisition of undeveloped properties (other than a
preliminary review of local mineral records).&nbsp; Investigations are generally
made, including in most cases receiving a title opinion of legal counsel,
before commencement of drilling operations.&nbsp; A thorough examination of title
has been made with respect to all of the Partnership's producing properties and
the Partnership believes that it has generally satisfactory title to such
properties.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><b><u>ITEM 3.&nbsp; LEGAL
PROCEEDINGS</u></b></p>



<p class=MsoNormal>The Partnership is not a
party to any legal proceedings.</p>



<p class=DMBodyText5 style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:
justify;text-indent:0in'>PDC, as Managing General Partner and operator of the
Partnership's wells, may be subject to various legal proceedings from time to
time arising in the normal course of business.&nbsp; Any outstanding and pending
legal actions are not considered material to the operations of the Partnership
or PDC.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><b><u>ITEM 4.&nbsp; SUBMISSION OF
MATTERS TO A VOTE OF SECURITY HOLDERS</u></b></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>None.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b>PART II</b></p>



<p class=MsoNormal><b><u>ITEM 5.&nbsp; MARKET FOR
REGISTRANT'S COMMON EQUITY AND RELATED STOCKHOLDER MATTERS</u></b></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>At
 December 31, 2005, the Partnership had 1,184 Investor Partners holding a total
of 1,451.54 units and one Managing General Partner.&nbsp; No established public
trading market exists for the units, nor will a public trading market ever
develop for the units.&nbsp; Limited and additional general partnership interests
are transferable, however, no assignee of units in the Partnership can become a
substituted partner without the written consent of the transferor and the
Managing General Partner.&nbsp; The Managing General Partner has not repurchased any
Partnership interests as of December 31, 2005.</p>

been derived from audited financial statements of the Partnership.&nbsp; See the

<p class=MsoNormal><b><u>ITEM 7. MANAGEMENT'S
DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS.</u></b></p>



<p class=MsoNormal>Safe Harbor Statement Under
the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Statements,
other than historical facts, contained in this Annual Report on Form 10-K,
including statements of estimated oil and gas production and reserves, future
cash flows and the Partnership's strategies, plans and objectives, are
&quot;forward-looking statements&quot; within the meaning of Section 27A of the
Securities Act of 1933, as amended (the &quot;Securities Act&quot;), and Section 21E of
the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &quot;Exchange Act&quot;).&nbsp; Although
the Partnership believes that its forward looking statements are based on
reasonable assumptions, it cautions that such statements are subject to a wide
range of risks, trends and uncertainties, incidental to the production and
marketing of oil and gas, that could cause actual results to differ materially
from those projected.&nbsp; Among those risks, trends and uncertainties are
important factors that could cause actual results to differ materially from the
forward looking statements, including, but not limited to, changes in
production volumes, worldwide demand and commodity prices for petroleum natural
resources; risks incidental to the operation of oil and gas wells; future
production and development costs; the effect of existing and future laws,
governmental regulations and the political and economic climate of the United
States; the effect of derivative activities; and conditions in the capital
markets.&nbsp; In particular, careful consideration should be given to cautionary
statements made in this Form 10-K and in the various reports the Partnership
has filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.&nbsp; The Partnership
undertakes no duty to update or revise these forward-looking statements.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>When
used in this Form 10-K, the words, &quot;expect,&quot; &quot;anticipate,&quot; &quot;intend,&quot; &quot;plan,&quot;
&quot;believe,&quot; &quot;seek,&quot; &quot;estimate&quot; and similar expressions are intended to identify
forward-looking statements, although not all forward-looking statements contain
these identifying words. Because these forward-looking statements involve risks
and uncertainties, actual results could differ materially from those expressed
or implied by these forward-looking statements for a number of important
reasons, including those discussed under &quot;Item 1A - Risk Factors&quot; and elsewhere
in this Form 10-K.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Restatement
of Historical Financial Statements</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership's financial statements have been restated to correct errors in the Partnership's
accounting for derivative transactions, asset retirement obligations, and certain aspects of its accounting
for oil and gas properties.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-13-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>


<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>A
summary of the adjustments included in the restatement and their impact on net
income and partners' equity for the year ended December 31, 2004, and for the
quarter ended March 31, 2005, is included in &quot;Item 1 - Business&quot; above.&nbsp; These
restatements had no effect on the Partnership's cash flows.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Detailed
information as to the effects of the restatements on the Partnership's
previously reported statements of operations and partners' equity and the
balance sheets as of and for the year ended December 31, 2004, and for each of
the quarters in 2004 and the first quarter of 2005 are presented in &quot;Note 10 -
Restatement of Historical Financial Statements&quot; in the Notes to the Financial
Statements.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Overview</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership was funded on April 30, 2004, with Investor Partner contributions
of $29,030,865 and the Managing General Partner's cash contribution of $6,419,029.&nbsp;
After payment of syndication costs of $2,919,286 and a one-time management fee
to the Managing General Partner of $435,463, the Partnership had available cash
of $32,095,145 with which to commence the Partnership's drilling activities.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
drilling of the Partnership's oil and gas wells commenced in May 2004,
following the funding of the Partnership.&nbsp; Drilling activities and completion
activities continued until the last of the thirty-seven wells in which the
Partnership participated was connected to a pipeline in December 2004.&nbsp; The
thirty-seven wells drilled by the Partnership are located in the State of Colorado within two oil and gas fields and all were completed as producing wells. &nbsp;The
wells produce predominantly natural gas along with associated crude oil.&nbsp; No
additional wells will be drilled and no additional development or exploratory
work will be undertaken because all of the funds from the initial capital
contributions of the partners were expended on the development of these
thirty-seven wells.&nbsp; </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Initial production from the Partnership's wells commenced
in June 2004 upon connecting the first well to a pipeline.&nbsp;&nbsp; Production and
sales of natural gas and oil from the Partnership's wells increased steadily
during the second half of 2004 as additional wells were completed and placed
into production, the last of which occurred in December 2004.&nbsp; </p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-14-<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all style='page-break-before:always'>
</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><i>Definitions:</i></p>

<ul style='margin-top:0in' type=disc>
 <li class=MsoNormal>Bbl - One barrel or 42 U.S.
     gallons of liquid volume.</li>
 <li class=MsoNormal>Mcf - One thousand cubic
     feet.</li>
 <li class=MsoNormal>Mcfe - One thousand cubic
     feet of natural gas equivalents, based on a ratio of 6 Mcf for each barrel
     of oil, which reflects the relative energy content.</li>
</ul>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>As
reflected in the table above, oil and gas sales increased by 116% over the
prior year.&nbsp; This increase was due to the increase in production of natural gas
and as the result of having all thirty-seven wells in production during 2005,
whereas, in 2004, the drilling of the Partnership's wells was in progress
during the months of May through December and did not reflect a full year of
production.&nbsp; A portion of the sales increase related to the increase in average
natural gas and oil prices that occurred during 2005. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Production
and operating costs for 2005 increased by 152% over the previous year, and is
due to the increase in production related activities with all wells producing
in 2005, as compared to 2004 when drilling activities were underway and fewer
wells were producing.&nbsp; The average of these costs in relation to natural gas
equivalent units (Mcfe) sold during the period increased to $1.04 per Mcfe in
2005 as compared to $0.73 in the previous year. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership manages oil and gas price risks through the use of derivative
instruments to provide protection on declining oil and natural gas prices.&nbsp; In
periods of rising oil and natural gas prices, the Partnership may record losses
in its derivative transactions as fair values exceed contract prices related to
the Partnership's oil and gas sales. &nbsp;In periods of declining prices, the
Partnership would theoretically record gains in its derivative transactions. &nbsp;Transactions
in derivative instruments resulted in net losses for both 2005 and 2004, with
2005 being greater as the result of the sharp rise in commodity prices for the
year.&nbsp; The total losses for both the net realized and the net unrealized losses
for 2005 were $1,129,266, as compared to $281,435 for 2004.&nbsp; The net losses are
comprised of the change in fair value of derivatives positions related to the
Partnership's oil and gas production for derivative contracts entered into by
the Managing General Partner on behalf of the Partnership.&nbsp; The Partnership
records gains or losses from its derivative positions on the statement of
operations as oil and gas price risk management gain (loss), net.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>Liquidity
and Capital Resources</i></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The Partnership had a working capital balance at December
31, 2005 of $2,740,273, which generally represents the receivables from oil and
gas sales for the preceding three months, offset by accounts payable from oil
and gas activity and short-term derivative values. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Future operations are expected to be funded from revenues
generated from oil and gas production activities.&nbsp; Current production revenues exceed operating costs by a
wide margin.&nbsp; The Partnership finished the drilling and completion of its
thirty-seven wells in December 2004 and all of the $32,095,145 available from
the initial partner contributions was utilized in this process.&nbsp; There are no
plans and no provision in the Partnership Agreement for additional development
or exploration beyond these thirty-seven wells, and there are no present
capital needs of the Partnership (see &quot;Item 1. Business - Plan of Operations&quot;
above).&nbsp; Under the Partnership Agreement, the Managing General Partner is
allowed to and may withhold production revenues in advance of significant
recompletion work on existing wells that may arise; however, the Partnership is
not permitted to borrow funds.&nbsp; If Partnership funds are used for recompletion
work, the cash distributions to the partners at the time of the recompletions
will be reduced, but should result in additional cash distributions following
the recompletions.</p>



<p class=DMBodyText5 style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:
justify;text-indent:0in'>The production
phase of operations will continue for the expected life of the wells and until
the wells can no longer be operated economically.&nbsp; As wells are produced, the
proceeds from the sale of oil and gas are collected and distributed, net of
operating costs, on a routine basis by the Managing General Partner and are not
retained by the Partnership.&nbsp; Normally, all available funds from the sales of
oil and gas, net of operating costs, are distributed monthly to the partners.&nbsp; </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>Oil
and Gas Reserves</i></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Information
related to the oil and gas reserves on the Partnership's wells is discussed in
detail in &quot;Note 7 - Supplemental Reserve Information (Unaudited)&quot; in the Notes
to Financial Statements.&nbsp; </p>





<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-15-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>




<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Quarterly
Analysis - 2005 Quarters versus 2004 Quarters</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>Overview</i></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
quarterly analysis presented below provides substantially all of the
information that would normally be contained in quarterly reports on Form 10-Q as
part of this Form 10-K.&nbsp; As explained in the Restatement of Historical
Financial Statements in &quot;Item 1 - Business&quot; above, this comprehensive Form 10-K
includes all annual and quarterly financial information for 2004 and 2005,
including restated information, in lieu of reporting in separately filed Forms
10-Q for the affected periods.&nbsp; </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Production and sales of natural gas and oil from the
Partnership's wells increased steadily during the second half of 2004 as wells
were drilled and placed into production.&nbsp; The last four of the thirty-seven
wells commenced production in the first quarter of 2005. &nbsp;The table below
reflects the Partnership's sales of production from the wells and the average
prices received for each of the quarters in 2004 and 2005.&nbsp; </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>&nbsp;</u></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Results
of Operations, Liquidity and Capital Resources - 2005 Quarters versus 2004
Quarters</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>As
reflected in the tables above, oil and gas sales for the first, second and
third quarters in 2005 reflect increases over the same quarter in the prior
year.&nbsp; This increase was due primarily to the increase in production of oil and
gas from having all thirty-seven wells in production during 2005, whereas, in
2004, the drilling of the Partnership's wells was in progress during the months
of May through December and all wells were not in production.&nbsp; A portion of the
sales increases related to the increase in average natural gas and oil prices
that occurred throughout 2005. Similarly, operating costs and depreciation, depletion
and amortization (DD&amp;A) increased in conjunction with the production and
sales increases for the quarters. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>With
the consistent overall trend of the quarterly results as explained in the
preceding paragraph, the following quarterly analysis and discussion of the
results of operations, liquidity and capital resources reflects only discussion
of those items that occurred in a particular quarter that deserve explanation
beyond that which applies in general to all quarters.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
average of production and operating costs in relation to natural gas equivalent
units (Mcfe) production was $1.04 per Mcfe in 2005 as compared to $0.73 in
2004, with ranges across the quarters from $0.71 in the third quarter of 2004 to
a high of $1.47 in the fourth quarter of 2005.&nbsp; This increase in average costs
was primarily due to increased severance and property taxes on the
significantly increased oil and gas sales prices along with additional well
workovers and production enhancement work performed.&nbsp; </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
discussion above under Item 7 captioned &quot;Liquidity and Capital Resources&quot; as of
December 31, 2005, generally applies to all quarters in 2004 and 2005.&nbsp; Only
the exceptions, if any, to the above discussion will be included in the
quarterly analysis below to avoid unnecessary repetition.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>Three
Month Periods Ended March 31 and June 30 - 2005 Compared to the Same Periods in
2004</i></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Drilling
of the Partnership's wells was not commenced until mid-2004 and no sales or
operating expenses were recorded in the first two quarters of 2004.&nbsp;
Consequently, there are no 2004 operating activities with which to compare 2005
operating results for these two quarters.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Expenses
in the second quarter of 2004 reflects a one-time management fee equal to 1&frac12;%
of investors' subscriptions, or $435,463, which was paid to the Managing
General Partner upon funding of the Partnership in April 2004 in accordance
with provisions of the Partnership Agreement.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>Three
Months Ended September 30 - 2005 Compared to the Same Period in 2004</i></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
increases in sales and operating costs in the third quarter of 2005 as compared
to 2004 occurred primarily due to the production volume increases in 2005 when
all wells were producing, while, in 2004, numerous wells began producing in the
third quarter but were not productive for the entire quarter since they did not
start producing until later in the quarter.&nbsp; As of September 30, 2004, a total
of thirty-two wells had been drilled and were producing as compared to the
thirty-seven wells producing as of September 30, 2005.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-17-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>


<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
decrease in DD&amp;A in the third quarter of 2005 as compared to 2004 occurred
primarily due to the higher production levels being offset by the depletion of
an increased reserve amount in the quarter, resulting in lower depreciation.&nbsp; The
increased reserve amount resulted from the use of actual reserve amounts in
2005 versus an estimated reserve amount in 2004.&nbsp; The increase in the total
reserves resulted from a revised estimation of reserves for 2005.&nbsp; See Note 7 -
&quot;Supplemental Reserve Information (Unaudited)&quot; for a more detailed discussion
on the reserves.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Transactions
in derivative instruments resulted in a net loss for the third quarter of 2005
of $1,295,271, as compared to a net loss of $172,186 in the same quarter in
2004.&nbsp; This change is generally due to the volume of derivative contracts as
well as rising prices compared to the contract price of the derivative
instrument. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Critical Accounting
Policies and Estimates</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>We
have identified the following policies as
critical to the understanding of the results of operations. This is not a
comprehensive list of all of our accounting policies. In many cases, the
accounting treatment of a particular transaction is specifically dictated by
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States with no need for
management's judgment in their application. There are also areas in which
management's judgment in selecting any available alternative would not produce
a materially different result. However, certain
accounting policies are important to the portrayal of the Partnership's
financial condition and results of operations and require management's most
subjective or complex judgments. In applying those policies, management uses
its judgment to determine the appropriate assumptions to be used in the
determination of certain estimates. Those estimates are based on our historical
experience, our observance of trends in the industry, and information available
from other outside sources as appropriate. For a more detailed discussion on
the application of these and other accounting policies, see &quot;Note 2 - Summary
of Significant Accounting Policies&quot; and other related notes in the Financial
Statements. The Partnership's critical accounting policies and estimates are as
follows:</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>Oil
and Gas Properties </i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>&nbsp;</i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The Partnership accounts for its oil and gas properties
under the successful efforts method of accounting.&nbsp; Costs of proved developed
producing properties, successful exploratory wells and development dry hole
costs are depreciated or depleted by the unit-of-production method based on
estimated proved developed producing oil and gas reserves.&nbsp; Property
acquisition costs are depreciated or depleted on the unit-of-production method
based on estimated proved oil and gas reserves.&nbsp; The Partnership obtains new
reserve reports from independent petroleum engineers annually as of December
31st of each year.&nbsp; The Partnership adjusts for any new drilling and
divestitures during the year as needed.&nbsp; The Partnership does not maintain an
inventory of undrilled leases.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-4.5pt;text-align:justify'>Upon sale or retirement of
significant portions of, or complete fields of, depreciable or depletable
property, the book value thereof less proceeds or salvage value, is credited or
charged to income.&nbsp; Upon sale of individual wells, the proceeds are credited to
property costs.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-4.5pt;text-align:justify'>Impairment testing for long-lived
assets is required when circumstances indicate those assets may be impaired.&nbsp;
The Partnership assesses impairment of capitalized costs of proved oil and gas
properties by comparing net capitalized costs to the estimated undiscounted
future net cash flows on a field-by-field basis using estimated production, and
based upon prices at which management reasonably estimates such products will
be sold. These estimates of future product prices may differ from current
market prices of oil and gas. Any downward revisions to the Partnership's
estimates of future production or product prices could result in an impairment
of the Partnership's oil and gas properties in subsequent periods. If net
capitalized costs exceed undiscounted future net cash flows, the measurement of
impairment is based on estimated fair value calculated using future discounted
cash flows.</p>



















<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-right:-4.5pt;text-align:center'>-18-</p>

<hr color="#000080"><br clear=all style='page-break-before:always'>


<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-right:-4.5pt;text-align:justify'><i>Revenue Recognition</i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>&nbsp;</i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Sales
of natural gas are recognized when natural gas has been delivered to a custody
transfer point, persuasive evidence of a sales arrangement exists, the rights
and responsibility of ownership pass to the purchaser, collection of revenue
from the sale is reasonably assured, and the sales price is fixed or
determinable.&nbsp; Natural gas is sold by the Managing General Partner under
contracts with terms ranging from one month up to the life of the well.&nbsp;
Virtually all of the Managing General Partner's contracts' pricing provisions
are tied to a market index with certain adjustments based on, among other
factors, whether a well delivers to a gathering or transmission line, quality
of natural gas and prevailing supply and demand conditions, so that the price
of the natural gas fluctuates to remain competitive with other available
natural gas supplies.&nbsp; As a result, the Partnership's revenues from the sale of
natural gas will suffer if market prices decline and benefit if they increase.&nbsp;
However, the Managing General Partner may from time to time enter into
derivative agreements, usually with a term of two years or less which may
either fix or collar a price in order to reduce the impact of market price
fluctuations. The Partnership believes that the pricing provisions of its
natural gas contracts are customary in the industry. </p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Managing General Partner currently uses the &quot;Net-Back&quot; method of accounting for
transportation arrangements of natural gas sales.&nbsp; The Managing General Partner
sells gas at the wellhead, collects a price, and recognizes revenues based on
the wellhead sales price since transportation costs downstream of the wellhead
are incurred by the Managing General Partner's customers and reflected in the
wellhead price.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Sales
of oil are recognized when persuasive evidence of a sales arrangement exists,
the oil is verified as produced and is delivered from storage tanks at well
locations to a purchaser, collection of revenue from the sale is reasonably
assured, and the sales price is determinable.&nbsp; The Partnership does not refine
any of its oil production.&nbsp; The Partnership's crude oil production is sold to
purchasers at or near the Partnership's wells under short-term purchase
contracts at prices and in accordance with arrangements that are customary in
the oil industry.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>&nbsp;</i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>Derivative
Financial Instruments</i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i>&nbsp;</i></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership accounts for derivative financial instruments in accordance with
FAS Statement No. 133 &quot;Accounting for Derivative Instruments and Certain
Hedging Activities&quot; as amended.&nbsp; During 2005 and 2004, none of the
derivative contracts qualified for hedge accounting under the terms of FAS No.
133.&nbsp; Accordingly, the derivative instruments are recorded as an asset or
liability on the balance sheet at fair value and the change in the fair value
is recorded in oil and gas price risk management gain (loss), net.&nbsp;
Because derivative arrangements are entered into by the Managing General
Partner on behalf of the Partnership, they are reported on the balance sheet as
a net short-term or long-term receivable due from or payable due to the
Managing General Partner.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
measurement of fair value is based on actively quoted market prices, if
available. Otherwise, the Managing General Partner seeks indicative price
information from external sources including broker quotes and industry
publications. If pricing information from external sources is not available,
measurement involves judgment and estimates. These estimates are based on
valuation methodologies considered appropriate by the Managing General Partner.
</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>By
using derivative financial instruments to manage exposures to changes in
commodity prices, the Partnership exposes itself to credit risk.&nbsp; Credit risk
is the failure of the counterparty to perform under the terms of the derivative
contract.&nbsp; When the fair value of a derivative contract is positive, the
counterparty owes the Managing General Partner, which in turn owes the
Partnership thus creating repayment risk.&nbsp; The Managing General Partner
minimizes the credit or repayment risk in derivative instruments by entering
into transactions with high-quality counterparties.</p>





















<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-19-</p>

<u><hr color="#000080"><br clear=all
style='page-break-before:always'>
</u>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><u>Recently
Issued Accounting Standards</u></p>



<p class=MsoBodyTextIndent style='text-indent:0in'>In June 2005, the FASB issued
SFAS No. 154, &quot;Accounting Changes and Error Corrections, a replacement of
APB Opinion No. 20 and FASB Statement No. 3,&quot; which replaces Accounting
Principles Board Opinion No. 20, &quot;Accounting Changes&quot; and SFAS No. 3,
&quot;Reporting Accounting Changes in Interim Financial Statements,&quot; and
changes the requirements for the accounting for and reporting of a change in
accounting principle. &nbsp;SFAS No. 154 requires retrospective application for
voluntary changes in accounting principle unless it is impracticable to do so,
and it applies to all voluntary changes in accounting principle.&nbsp; SFAS No. 154
is effective for accounting changes and corrections of errors made in fiscal
years beginning after December 15, 2005. Consequently, we will adopt the provisions of SFAS 154 for our fiscal year beginning January 1, 2006. &nbsp;We currently believe that adoption of the provisions of SFAS No. 154 will not have a
material impact on our financial statements.</p>



<p class=MsoBodyTextIndent style='text-indent:0in'>In September 2006, the FASB
issued SFAS No. 157, &quot;Fair Value Measurements,&quot; which replaces several
existing pronouncements, defines fair value, establishes a framework for
measuring fair value, and expands disclosures about fair value measurements.&nbsp;
SFAS No. 157 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning
after November 15, 2007, and interim periods within those fiscal years.&nbsp;
Consequently, we will adopt the provisions of SFAS 157 for our fiscal year
beginning January 1, 2008.&nbsp; The Partnership is currently evaluating the impact
of the provisions of SFAS No. 157 on its financial statements.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><b><u>Item
7A.&nbsp;&nbsp;Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosure About Market Risk</u></b></p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Market-Sensitive
Instruments and Risk Management</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Partnership's primary market risk exposure is commodity price risk for the oil
and gas the Partnership produces and sells.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Commodity Price Risk</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
Managing General Partner utilizes commodity-based derivative instruments,
entered into on behalf of the Partnership, to manage a portion of the
Partnership's exposure to price risk from oil and natural gas sales.&nbsp; These
instruments consist of CIG (Colorado Interstate Gas) index-based contracts
traded by JP Morgan for Colorado natural gas production. These derivative
instruments have the effect of locking in for specified periods (at
predetermined prices or ranges of prices) the prices the Managing General
Partner will receive for the volume of oil and natural gas to which the
derivative relates.&nbsp; As a result, while these derivative instruments are
structured to reduce Partnership's exposure
to changes in price associated with the derivative commodity, they also limit
the benefit the Partnership might otherwise have received from price changes
associated with the commodity.&nbsp; The Partnership has adopted the policy of the
Managing General Partner prohibiting the use of oil and natural gas future and
option contracts for speculative purposes.&nbsp; Derivative arrangements are
entered into by the Managing General Partner on behalf of the Partnership and
are reported on the Partnership's balance sheet at fair value as a net
short-term or long-term receivable due from or payable to the Managing General
Partner.&nbsp; Changes in the fair value of the Partnership's share of derivatives
are recorded in the statement of operations. The following table summarizes the
Partnership's share of open derivative positions as of December 31, 2005 and
2004.</p>





























<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'>-20-</p>

style='page-break-before:always'>

is 15 months.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The
annual average Colorado Interstate Gas closing price for natural gas for 2005
was $6.96 per MMBtu.&nbsp; The average NYMEX closing price for oil for 2005 was
$55.34 per barrel.&nbsp; Future near-term gas and oil prices will be affected by
various supply and demand factors such as weather, government and environmental
regulations and new drilling activities within the industry.</p>



<p class=MsoNormal><u>Disclosure of Limitations</u></p>



<p class=MsoNormal>As the information above
incorporates only those exposures that exist at December 31, 2005, it does not
consider those exposures or positions which could arise after that date. As a
result, the Partnership's ultimate realized gain or loss with respect to
commodity price fluctuations will depend on the exposures that arise during the
period, and the Partnership's hedging strategies and commodity prices at the
time.</p>
